  "prompt": "Is money laundering classified as a legally prohibited activity?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is classified as a legally prohibited activity. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (i.e., \"dirty money\") appear legitimate (i.e., \"clean\"). This is typically done by disguising the true origin of funds through a series of transactions or financial operations.\n\nMost countries have strict laws and regulations against money laundering. For example:\n\n1. **United States**: The Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the USA PATRIOT Act impose anti-money laundering (AML) requirements on financial institutions.\n2. **European Union**: The EU has multiple Anti-Money Laundering Directives that member states must implement.\n3. **International**: The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets international standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include severe fines, imprisonment, and other legal consequences for individuals and organizations involved in such activities.",
